Possible scenarios where c16rtomb produces multibyte sequence with a size greater than 2

According to cppreference:

size_t c16rtomb( char* restrict s, char16_t c16, mbstate_t* restrict ps );
Converts a single code point from its variable-length 16-bit wide character representation (typically, UTF-16) to its narrow multibyte character representation.

From my humble understanding, this means that c16rtomb can convert a utf16 character into a multibyte sequence of variable length, which means that the amount of bytes written to s might be more than two, a fact stressed upon once more by this line from the webpage:

At most MB_CUR_MAX bytes can be written by this function.

This seems illogical to me.
I am well aware that the current locale at the point of calling the function is important, and I am also aware of the existence of surrogate pairs (emojis, accented letters etc), but it still doesn't make any sense. The utf16 code point is passed using a single char16_t character, not a pointer which could be interpreted as a string, and therefore, a surrogate pair. This means that only one valid 16 bit character can be passed to this function. I have even tried passing both high and low surrogate of the rocket emoji (🚀) to the function with the hope of producing such a situation like in the snippet below:
#include <stdio.h>
#include <locale.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <uchar.h>

int main()
{
    char16_t ch = '\xd8\x3d';
    char16_t cl = '\xd3\x80';
    size_t sz = 0;
    char s[2];

    setlocale(LC_ALL, "en_US.UTF-8");

    sz = c16rtomb(s, ch, NULL);
    printf("ch: %ld\n", sz);

    sz = c16rtomb(s, ch, NULL);
    printf("cl: %ld\n", sz);
}

which does not produce the intended 'greater than two bytes written' case:
ch: 0
cl: -1

Are there any scenarios where the function writes more than one byte? Will using setlocale prevent such a situation from happening? Or am I misunderstanding something?
Bear with me, as I'm still relatively new to all this unicode business.

